# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acheulean
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It is the *chef-lieu* of one of the arrondissements of Somme.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Located on the river Somme, it was the capital of Ponthieu.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is located on the river Somme, 20 km (12 mi) from its modern mouth in the English Channel.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The majority of the town is located on the east bank of the Somme, as well as on an island.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It is located at the head of the Abbeville Canal, and is 45 km (28 mi) northwest of Amiens and approximately 200 kilometres (120 mi) from Paris.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It is also 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) as the crow flies from the Baie de Somme and the English Channel.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the medieval period, it was the lowest crossing point on the Somme and it was nearby that Edward III's army crossed shortly before the Battle of Crécy in 1346.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Just halfway between Rouen and Lille, it is the historical capital of the County of Ponthieu and maritime Picardy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville station is served by trains on the line between Boulogne-sur-Mer and Amiens and between Calais and Paris.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the southern terminus of the Réseau des Bains de Mer, the line to Dompierre-sur-Authie opened on 19 June 1892 and closed on 10 March 1947.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is located just near the A16 autoroute, and is about 1 hour 50 minutes by car from Paris.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville has an oceanic climate due to its proximity to the ocean.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The summers and winters are temperate and rainy, days of snow are fairly common (18 days of snow per year on average).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] There are 26 days of storm per year with a maximum in the months of July and August, the rains are frequent and distributed regularly in the year with precipitation totalling 781.3 millimetres (30.76 in) and 128 days with precipitation.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The highest temperature was 37.8 °C (100.0 °F) on 1 July 1952 and the record low is −17.4 °C (0.7 °F), which occurred during a particularly cold spell on 17 January 1985.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Its inhabitants are called *Abbevillois* in French.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The population of the commune is relatively old.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is the seat of the Chambre de commerce et d'industrie d'Abbeville – Picardie maritime.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It manages ports, the aerodrome and industrial areas of the arrondissement of Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville manufactured textiles, and in particular, linens and tablecloths when the Van Robais family created la Manufacture Royale des Rames in 1665; however after the Edict of Nantes was revoked and the subsequent migration of Protestants away from the area, the cloth business succumbed.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Also affecting the economy of the town was the closure of the river port on the Somme River due to excessive silt.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It also has cordage factories, carpet factories, and spinning mills.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was awarded three flowers in 2007 by the *Conseil des Villes et Villages Fleuris de France* [Council of Floral Cities and Villages of France] in the Contest of floral cities and villages.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville has featured as the departure point for Stage 4 of the 2012 Tour de France and the departure point for Stage 1 of the 2011 Tour de Picardie.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The commune has also been on the route of the Grand Prix de la Somme one-day cycle race.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville will feature as the departure point for Stage 6 of the 2015 Tour de France, on 9 July.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Victor Hugo evoked the trips he made to Abbeville in his accounts of travel.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Collegiate Church of Saint-Vulfran is portrayed in the short story "Casting the Runes," by M.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] James, as the site of a mysterious death.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] André Maurois, in *Les Silences du Colonel Bramble* (1918) amusingly described the intact commercial spirit of the inhabitants of Abbeville in the last months of the war.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Maurois' *Ni ange ni bete* (Neither Angel, Nor Beast) is also set in Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Christian Morel de Sarcus, in his novel *Déluges*, Éditions Henry, November 2004 (2005 Prix Renaissance), evokes the bombing of 1940 and the floods of the Somme of 2001.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Romans occupied it and named it *Abbatis Villa*.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] There are also *Hableville* in 1607 and *Ableville* in 1643, with transitional addition of an L.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville boasted of having never been taken and was called *Abbeville la pucelle* ("the virgin").
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It was also granted many privileges from the Capetian kings, to reward its loyalty.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The blason populaire of the people of Abbeville is *"chés bourgeois d'Adville"*.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the capital of the former province of Ponthieu.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Today, it is one of the three sub-prefectures of the Somme department.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The commune is part of the Communauté d'agglomération de la Baie de Somme of which it has the headquarters.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The subsoil contains many vestiges of the Pleistocene.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] This discovery was a founding element of prehistory as a science.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The name Abbeville has been adopted to name a category of Paleolithic stone tools.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] These stone tools are also known as handaxes.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Various handaxes were found near Abbeville by Jacques Boucher de Perthes starting in 1838 and he was the first to describe the stones in detail, pointing out in the first publication of its kind, in 1846, that the stones were chipped deliberately by early man, so as to form a tool.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Some of these artifacts are displayed at the Musee Boucher-de-Perthes.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] A more refined and later version of handaxe production was found in the Abbeville/Somme River district.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The more refined handaxe became known as the Acheulean industry, named after Saint-Acheul, today a suburb of Amiens.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It retained some importance into the Bronze Age.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Although the research of Jacques Boucher de Perthes has highlighted an occupation of the site of Abbeville (*Menchecourt-les-Abbeville* quarter) from the Acheulean era, in Roman times it was a succession of marshes, similar to marsh of *Saint-Gilles* which remains today.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Further to the north, the entire plateau between the Authie and the Somme was covered in primary forest.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Romans had to break through this forest massif for the passage of the road from Amiens to the village of Ponches on the one hand, and on the other to the west by the road linking the Beauvaisis in Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The couple Abbeville / Saint-Valery-sur-Somme is the key to the historical enigma of the landing of Magnus Maximus and his Britto-Roman troops in the spring of 383 AD (St-Valery = Leuconos > Pors Liogan; Abbeville = Talence > Tolente).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The road to Paris passes near the Vieux-Rouen-sur-Bresle, which has been identified with the character Himbaldus (Château-Hubault).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the 7th century, the Benedictine monks of Saint-Valéry, Saint-Josse, Saint-Saulve de Montreuil, Forest-Montiers, Balance and Valloires cleared the woods that were close to their monasteries.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Frankish king Dagobert I then gave part of the forest of Crécy, the hermitage became the Abbey of Saint-Riquier: it is the Act of birth of the abbatial field of Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The name, Abbeville, comes from the Latin and means "*town* (or more exactly) *field of Abbots*" (of Saint-Riquier).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The first historical mention of Abbeville, in the chronicle of Hariulf, dates to 831 AD.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It was a small island in the Somme, inhabited by fishermen who took refuge there with their boats and had fortified it against barbarian invasions from the north.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Abbot Angilbert built a castle to defend this island, which depended on the Abbey of Saint-Riquier.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It was an important fort city responsible for the defense of the Somme.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 992, Hugh Capet fortified the city and gave it to his daughter, Gisèle, on her marriage to Hugh I, Count of Ponthieu who resided in Montreuil.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] From the 12th century, the Abbot opened a leprosy hospice, the *maladrerie des Frères du Val*, moved to Grand-Laviers in the following century, before urban sprawl.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Then accessible to boats, Abbeville became a port of the English Channel under the dependence of the Abbots of Saint-Riquier.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Subsequently, the silting up of the Bay of Somme forced the sea to recede by 12 kilometres (7.5 mi), but the city continued to be a trading port.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville became the capital of the Ponthieu and rapidly spread on both banks of the River Somme, right on the slope of the hillsides and left into the marshes.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1095, Guy I Count of Ponthieu founded the Abbey Saint-Pierre of Abbeville and on 24 May 1098, he was dubbed as a Knight by Louis the Fat.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On the occasion of the First Crusade, Abbeville was the meeting point of many troops from the northern provinces.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Godefroy de Bouillon reviewed them on the current location of the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] To commemorate the event, they built a belfry in 1126.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] A century later, Jeanne de Dammartin, Countess of Ponthieu (1220–1278), allowed the religious to convert an additional part of forests into cropland, allowing the development of the local economy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Afterwards it was governed by the Counts of Ponthieu.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Together with that county, it came into the possession of the Alençon and other French families, and afterwards into that of the House of Castile.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1214, the Abbeville militia took part in the Battle of Bouvines.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the middle of the 13th century, Abbeville was "one of the best cities of the Kings of France".
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Its port was one of the first of the Kingdom and its considerable trade.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1259, the Estates-General of the Kingdom stood at Abbeville and Henry III of England has met with Louis IX of France to sign the Treaty of Paris, which settled the question of the conquests of Philip Augustus.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1272, Ponthieu with Abbeville, passed by marriage to the kings of England, but Philip V took over the city, claiming that Edward II of England had not fulfilled its duty of vassal.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Edward II complied with the feudal law, and Abbeville fell under English rule.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However many challenges rose between the bourgeois and their new masters.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Throughout the Hundred Years' War, the town was alternately occupied by English and French forces, causing the inhabitants of the town enormous suffering.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] They were tested by excessive taxes and terrible epidemics.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Over the decades, the region was devastated by looting, epidemics and wolves.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The city thus appealed to the King of France twice, in 1406 and in 1415.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Affected by the English expedition of 1346, Abbeville resisted the English army, and served as a home base for Jean Marant who refuelled Calais besieged by the English.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1360, it was transferred, with the County of Ponthieu of which it was the capital, to the Crown of England by the Treaty of Brétigny.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] That same year, John II of France stayed there after returning from captivity.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1361, Abbeville, again English, poorly welcomed its new masters.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Ringois, a bourgeois of the city, refusing to take the oath of obedience to Edward III of England, was taken to English soil and hurled from the top of the Tower of Dover Castle into the sea in 1368.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During this period, a revolt of Jacques was defeated by the Abbeville militia in the vicinity of Saint-Riquier.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The soldiers of Charles V captured the city by surprise, but the English recaptured it shortly after and it remained in their possession until 1385.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Like other Picardy cities, it then passed under Burgundian rule at the end of the Battle of Mons-en-Vimeu in 1421.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1430, Henry VI of England was received at Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1435, the city was ceded to Philip the Good, the Duke of Burgundy, by the Treaty of Arras.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Louis XI bought Abbeville from Philip the Good in 1463 and visited the city on 27 September of the same year.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In December, by letters patent, he confirmed the privileges of the city, attached by his predecessors, but in 1465 Charles the Bold revoked the grant by taking the lead of the League of the Public Weal.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1466, the municipality enacted safety regulations recommending to reduce or not use flammable materials (such as walls in timber or straw roofs) in construction, in order to reduce the risk of fire.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However, it clashed with general hostility, and the regulations were finally just applied.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Louis XI failed before Abbeville in 1471, but recovered Picardy on the death of the Duke of Burgundy in 1477.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1477 it was annexed by King Louis XI, and was held by two illegitimate branches of the royal family in the 16th and 17th centuries, being in 1696 reunited to the crown.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1480, then 1483, a plague epidemic ravaged Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 3 October 1514, Louis XII married Mary Tudor in Abbeville, the daughter of Henry VII of England.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 23 June 1517, Francis I came to Abbeville with the Queen and met Cardinal Wolsey, representing the King of England, to form a league against Charles V.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1523, the English finally fell alongside Charles V in the wars of Francis I and the city had to suffer many frequent requisitions.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] That same year, an outbreak of plague ravaged Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] A further epidemic of plague struck Abbeville in 1582.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1531, Francis I performed a new tour in the city.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The most serious blows to Abbeville were the series of English raids by the Duke of Suffolk on the sides of the estuary in 1544, after the fall of Boulogne and Montreuil.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] King Henry II was received in Abbeville in 1550.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During the Wars of Religion, the Protestant governor was massacred with his family, by the people.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1568, François Cocqueville, a Protestant leader of war, entered the Ponthieu with 3,000 soldiers.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] He plundered and sacked the Abbey of Dommartin, towns, churches and castles of Authie and Saint-Valery-sur-Somme region.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Chased by the Marshal de Brissac, Cocqueville was captured with several of his own and they were beheaded in the marketplace of Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Bartholomew's Day massacre caused no casualties in Abbeville due to the moderation of Léonor d'Orléans, the Duke of Longueville and governor of Picardy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However, Abbeville had embraced the Catholic League and suffered from the Wars of Religion0, and it was relieved when it was recognised, by Henry IV in April 1594, despite the clergy who persisted in its resistance.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Following this, on 18 December 1594, the King of France Henry IV visited Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] At the beginning of the 17th century a plague epidemic wreaked havoc.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] More than 8,000 people perished, thus depopulating Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 21 December 1620, King Louis XIII visited the town.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] His sister Henrietta went there several times.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1635 and 1636 the town suffered from the war against the Holy Roman Empire and Spain.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] They destroyed many villages located in the surrounding area.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Richelieu stayed in the city in October.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] A plague epidemic raged again during the years 1635, 1636 and 1637.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1656, 6,000 soldiers, who had participated in the English Civil War, landed in France and took their quarters in Abbeville from where they left to go and reinforce the army of Turenne en route to Valenciennes.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Shortly after, Balthazar de Fargues sold the place to John of Austria and after meeting the price, he refused to deliver it to him, raising troops for himself who were then spread throughout the Ponthieu to ransom the inhabitants.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Finally stopped, he was tried and hanged at *Place Saint-Pierre* on 17 March 1665.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1657, Louis XIV came twice to Abbeville with his mother, Anne of Austria.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] By the mid-16th century, the woad trade shrank after the promotion of the pastel of the Pays du Midi, and it took to restructuring crafts.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Colbert used it, and under Louis XIV, the city developed through the installation of Van Robais, manufacturers of sheets and tapestries from the Netherlands who, in 1665, created the Manufacture royale des Rames (drapery workshops).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1685, it suffered a serious blow at the Revocation of the Edict of Nantes, the Protestant temple was destroyed and the persecuted workers who were the majority of skilled labour left the town, including those of Van Robais.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The population decreased very strongly and never fully recovered from this exodus of talent.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1693 Ponthieu became the refuge of a considerable number of Bretons and Normans who had left their country because of famine, but they almost all perished of misery.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] At the end of the reign of Louis XIV the country was covered with troops.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1708, after the capture of Lille, the troops of the Duke of Marlborough and Eugene of Savoy came forward frequently at the gates of Abbeville, ransoming the farms and villages.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The winter of 1709 was terrible; people perished from cold, hunger and misery.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] At this time industry was quite dark and the State was required to help sheets manufacturers.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1717, Russian monarch Peter the Great passed through Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In July 1766, the Chevalier de La Barre, accused of having, a year earlier, failed to give a due salute to a religious procession for Corpus Christi by refusing to remove his hat and singing ungodly songs.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However, the story is more complex and revolves around a mutilated cross.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] He was executed on the *Place du Grand-Marché* for blasphemy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Subject to the issue, his legs were crushed.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The right hand and the determined language, his decapitated corpse was finally delivered to the flames with the *Dictionnaire philosophique* of Voltaire on the same place.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Today, a paving stone, engraved with his name and the date of his execution, is visible on the place of execution (*Place Max-Lejeune*), near the town hall.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The martyrdom of the Chevalier de La Barre served as Voltaire's banner in his fight against religious fanaticism.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 2 November 1773, the powder magazine exploded killing 150 people and damaging nearly 1,000 houses.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Administratively, the people of Abbeville formed a subdelegation whose competence has been confused with that of the delegation of the same name (located in the Generalitat of Amiens).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On the eve of the Revolution, Abbeville was the chef-lieu of a main electoral Bailiwick (without secondary Bailiwick).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was fairly important in the 18th century, when the Van Robais Royal Manufacture (one of the first major factories in France) brought great prosperity (but some class controversy) to the town.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] There were no significant excesses during periods of Revolution and the Terror.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1793, on *Place Saint-Pierre* the furniture of the churches was burned, along with images and the feudal titles.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Church of Saint-vulfran became the Temple of Reason.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 8 June 1794, a festival was celebrated in honour of the Supreme Being.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville suffered from famine in 1794 and 1795.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 5 January 1795, the Hotel of Grutuze, built under Charles VII, attended by the directors of the district, was destroyed by a fire.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1797, the Society of Emulation of Abbeville, one of the oldest learned societies of France, was created.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1798 and 1799, the winter was severe and a part of the town was flooded.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 18 brumaire year X (9 November 1801), there was a terrible hurricane that caused more than 1,300,000 francs worth of damage in the arrondissement.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 29 prairial year XI (18 June 1803), Napoleon passed through the town for the first time.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During the preparations of the expedition he was planning against the United Kingdom, the First Consul often spent time in Abbeville by going to the camp of Boulogne.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1813, as part of the reorganisation of the cavalry which had been decimated in Russia, the arrondissement offered the government 43 men mounted and equipped.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Early in 1814, with invasion becoming more imminent every day, the urban National Guard was reorganised across the whole of the Empire.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] 30 pieces of artillery were placed on the walls, and to complete the defense system, trees were felled in the vicinity to make 30,000 palisades and 14,000 shields.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 20 February, a column of cavalry forming the vanguard of the 3rd Corps of the Prussian army, commanded by Baron de Geismar, arrived in Doullens, before heading to Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Immediately, the Abbevillois ran to arms.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] 800 rifles were made available and a vigorous resistance began when the population learned that this supposed vanguard of the Prussian army had more than 1,500 to 2,000 men in its ranks, both Cossacks and Saxon Lancers, who eventually made their way to Paris.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In early April, after the Battle of Paris and the abdication of Napoleon, 2,000 Lancers and Prussian cuirassiers commanded by General Röder arrived from Paris and the surrounding countryside, and committed all kinds of excesses during their stay.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 27 April 1814, Louis XVIII entered the town and was received with an outpouring of joy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During the First Restoration, many distinguished people and about 10,000 British troops passed through Abbeville, to return to their country.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Duke of Berry, accompanied by the 10th Regiment of Cuirassiers and the 108th Infantry Regiment, stayed there.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 21 March 1815, King Louis XVIII, who was on the way to exile, spent a night in the town.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1815, after the Battle of Waterloo, the town was again put into defence.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However, after numerous desertions, the garrison was reduced to 400 men.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Victor Hugo came to Abbeville three times, as a tourist: In 1835, he stayed there successively from 26 July (after going down to *L'Écu de Brabant*), then on 4 and 5 August (staying at *L'Hôtel d'Angleterre*).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In August and September 1837, he came to Amiens after having descended the Somme by Steamboat.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Finally, in 1849, leaving the city in the rain on 11 September.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1847, there was the arrival of the railway in Abbeville with the opening of the Amiens-Abbeville section of the line of the Longueau–Boulogne railway.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1856, the Abbeville railway station was inaugurated, which is still in service.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the birthplace of Rear Admiral Amédée Courbet (1827–1885), whose victories on land and at sea made him a national hero during the Sino-French War (August 1884 to April 1885).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Courbet died in June 1885, shortly after the end of the war, at Makung in the Pescadores Islands, and his body was brought back to France and buried in Abbeville on 1 September 1885 after a state funeral at Les Invalides a few days earlier.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville's old Haymarket Square (Place du Marché-au-Blé) was renamed Place de l'Amiral Courbet in July 1885, shortly after the news of Courbet's death reached France, and an extravagant baroque statue of Courbet was erected in the middle of the square at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The statue was damaged in a devastating German bombing raid during World War II.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It was an allied base during World War I.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 13 August 1892, the Ortiz gang committed a burglary there.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1896, the Socialist Jules Guesde came to lecture in Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the aftermath, a group of the French Workers' Party and a House of the people are created.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] 1899, the phone has already arrived in Abbeville but its operation does not any satisfaction.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1899, Abbeville industry had a mill, a table linen factory, a rope factory, a factory of weight scales, three smelters, a boiler works, a locksmith for buildings, a wood grinding mill, a distillery, etc.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 7 July 1907 was the inauguration of the La Barre Monument, gathering many Republicans, delegates from Socialist groups and free-thinkers.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During World War I, the town was never occupied by the German troops (as evidenced by the monument built on the Mont de Caubert).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1916, during the Battle of the Somme, it served as a military hospital (the 3rd Australian General Hospital).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] As with Amiens and Beauvais, the town was partially destroyed and the aftermath of war is significant nearby, particularly due to unexploded ordnance still found in the soil.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In 1918, it was the seat of two Anglo-French conferences (conferences of Abbeville): That of 25 March, between Field Marshal Haig and Generals Wilson and Foch, who convened the Doullens conference.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] During the second conference on 2 May, Foch demanded authority on the Italian front but only obtained a power of coordination.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It was at the Conference of Abbeville (1 and 2 May 1918) while the armies weakened that Foch opposite Clemenceau and Lloyd George would have considered a fallback to the south to protect the capital.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the event that the French and British armies were separated and they could no longer defend both access to the ports of the English Channel and Paris, the British army would have then withdrawn and stood on the Somme.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 31 May 1918, American war poet John Allan Wyeth was a Second Lieutenant in the 33rd U.S.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Infantry Division, which was largely composed of soldiers from the Illinois Army National Guard.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Wyeth and his fellow Doughboys were stationed in nearby Huppy, when German aeroplanes began a bombing raid on Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] At the time, such air raids were a nightly affair and Abbeville was in the process of being evacuated.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Wyeth later versified his memories of the air raid in the sonnet *Huppy*.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 3 May 1936, voters in the 1st District of Abbeville did not derogate from a broad popular movement.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the 2nd round, they chose Max Lejeune as the MP who, at 27 years old, was the youngest elected to the chamber.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 12 September 1939 the Abbeville Conference took place in which France and the United Kingdom decided to not continue the attack on Germany, which resulted in a tougher situation on eastern front.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 9 May 1940, authorities in Belgium arrested a number of both far right and far left activists and put them in custody of a French Army unit stationed near Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 20 May, when the advancing German Army cut off the area (see following), a group of French soldiers carried out a massacre and killed a number of members of the right wing Verdinaso and Rexist Party and of the Belgian Communist Party.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Altogether, twenty two suspects of varying political stripe were selected and executed without trial.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the development of the 1940 Battle of France, the Germans had massed the bulk of their armoured force in Panzer Group von Kleist, which attacked through the comparatively unguarded sector of the Ardennes and achieved a breakthrough at Sedan with air support.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The group raced to the coast of the English Channel at Abbeville, thus isolating (20 May 1940) the British Expeditionary Force, Belgian Army, and some divisions of the French Army in northern France.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Charles de Gaulle (17–18 May 1940), then a colonel, launched a counterattack in the region of Laon (see the map) with 80 tanks to destroy the communication of the German armoured troops.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] His newly formed 4e Division cuirassée reached Montcornet, resulting in the Battle of Montcornet.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Without support, the 4th DCR was forced to retreat.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Abbeville massacre took place on 20 May 1940.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was taken by the Germans from the 2nd Panzer Division of Generalmajor Rudolf Veiel, also on 20 May 1940.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] There was another counter-attack with the Battle of Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] After Laon (24 May), de Gaulle was promoted to temporary general: "On 28 May (...) the 4th DCR attacked twice to destroy a pocket captured by the enemy south of the Somme near Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The operation was successful, with over 400 prisoners taken and the entire pocket mopped up except for Abbeville (...) but in the second attack the 4th DCR failed to gain control of the city in the face of superior enemy numbers." The Germans were forced back about 50 kilometres (31 mi).
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Allied Aerodrome Abbeville was used by the German Luftwaffe during most of the war.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] After five years, in September 1944, Abbeville was liberated by the Polish 1st Armoured Division (which was attached to the 1st Canadian Army) under General Stanisław Maczek, which entered Abbeville through the suburb of Rouvroy.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] World War II was not kind to the architecture of the town as the famous 17th-century Gothic Cathedral of St.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It, along with the town hall with its tower from the 13th century were saved, albeit damaged.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] In the spring of 2001, the city, like the Somme Valley, had to suffer floods.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] These lasted several weeks, because of the saturation of the water table, the result of a year of exceptional precipitation.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The station was inaccessible, the tracks being covered by several centimetres of water.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The city was very picturesque until the early days of the Second World War when it was bombed mostly to rubble in one night by the German Army.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The town overall is now mostly modern and rebuilt.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Collegiate Church of Saint-Vulfran (Wulfram of Sens) was constructed from 1488 and into the 16th and 17th centuries, although the original design was not completed.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The nave has only two bays and the choir is insignificant.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] However, the façade is a masterpiece of flamboyant Gothic architecture, which made the city famous, and is flanked by two Gothic towers.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Wulfram, its patron saint who is celebrated on 20 March, was born c.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] 650 AD, in Milly (Gâtinais), and was Lord at the Court of Chlothar III, Abbot of Fontenelle, Archbishop of Sens in 682, and an evangeliser of Frisia.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] He died at Saint-Wandrille (Fontenelle Abbey) in 720.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The building was classified as a historical monument in 1840.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Built in 1911, the theatre is one of the few in the region that boasts an Italian room.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Registered as an historical monument in 2003.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Classified as a World Heritage Site in 2005 and registered as an historic monument in 1926, the belfry is one of the oldest in France, built in 1209.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] On 20 May 1940, during a bombing, its roof was damaged and it was only in 1986 that it was rebuilt.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The belfry is one of the fifty-six belfries of Belgium and France registered in 2005 by the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO in recognition of its testimony to the rise of municipal power in the region and its architecture.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It has housed the museum of the city since 1954.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Boucher de Perthes Museum is partly situated in the now unused bell tower of the 13th century which is inscribed on the World Heritage list.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] It is a tribute to Jacques Boucher de Crèvecœur de Perthes who also has a lycée named after him.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The museum features artwork and artifacts from the 16th century onwards, along with other exhibitions that periodically change.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Classified as an historic monument in 1986, the Manufacture des Rames specialised in the production of luxury linen.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The building was partly constructed in 1710.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The Church of the Holy Sepulchre, situated in the heart of the old town centre, is a collegiate Gothic church from the 11th century.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The thirty-one stained glass windows were designed by Alfred Manessier (1911–1993) and were made in Chartres.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The church was classified as an historical monument in 1907.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] The La Barre Monument was erected in 1907 by public subscription, in commemoration of the martyrdom of the Chevalier de La Barre.
[src:acheulean/abbeville-p01] Located near the station, next to the bridge on the Somme canal, the La Barre Monument is an annual rallying point, on the first Sunday of July, for defenders of secularism and freethinkers.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The original artifacts were collected from road construction sites on the Somme river near Abbeville by a French customs officer, Boucher de Perthes.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Subsequently, Louis Laurent Gabriel de Mortillet (1821–1898), professor of prehistoric anthropology at the School of Anthropology in Paris, published (1882) "*Le Prehistorique, antiquité de l'homme*", in which he was the first to characterize periods by the name of a site.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Chellean included artifacts discovered at the town of Chelles, a suburb of Paris.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] They are similar to those found at Abbeville.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Later anthropologists substituted Abbevillian for Chellean, the latter of which is no longer in use.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Abbevillian tool users were the first archaic humans in Europe, classified as either late Homo erectus as Homo antecessor or as Homo heidelbergensis.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The label Abbevillian prevailed until the Leakey family discovered older (yet similar) artifacts at Olduvai Gorge (a.k.a.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Oldupai Gorge), starting in 1959, and promoted the African origin of man.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Olduwan (or Oldowan) soon replaced Abbevillian in describing African and Asian paleoliths.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The term Abbevillian is still used, but it is now restricted to Europe.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The label, however, continues to lose popularity as a scientific designation.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Mortillet had portrayed his traditions as chronologically sequential.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] In the Abbevillian, early Palaeolithic hominins used cores; in the Acheulian, flakes.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Olduwan tools, however, indicate that in the earliest Palaeolithic, the distinction between flake and core is less clear.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Consequently, there also is a tendency to view Abbevillian as an early phase of Acheulian.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The Abbevillian type site is on the 150-foot terrace of the River Somme.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Tools found there are rough chipped bifacial handaxes made during the Elsterian Stage of the Pleistocene Ice Age, which covered central Europe between 478,000 and 424,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The Abbevillian is a phase of Olduwan that occurred in Europe near, but not at, the end of the Lower Palaeolithic (2.5 mya. – 2,500,000 years ago).
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Those who adopt the Abbevillian scheme refer to it as the middle Acheulian, about 600,000-500,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Geologically it occurred in the Middle Pleistocene, younger than about 700,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] It spanned the Günz-Mindel interglacial period between the Günz and the Mindel, but more recent finds of the East Anglian Palaeolithic push the date back into the Günz, closer to the 700,000 ya mark.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The Abbevillian culture bearers are not believed to have evolved in Europe, but to have entered it from further east.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] It was thus preceded by the earlier Olduwan of Homo erectus, and the Upper Acheulian, of which Clactonian and Tayacian are considered phases, supplanted it.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The Acheulian there went on into the Levalloisian and Mousterian are associated with Neanderthal man.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] To avoid the question of what culture name should be used to describe European artifacts, some, such as Schick and Toth, refer to "non-handaxe" and "handaxe" sites.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Handaxes came into use at about the 500,000 ya mark.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] Non-handaxe sites are often the same sites as handaxe sites, the difference being one of time, or, if geographically different, have no discernible spatial pattern.
[src:acheulean/abbevillian] The physical evidence is summarized in the table below Note that the dates assigned vary widely after 700,000 ya and, except where substantiated by scientific methods, should be viewed as tentative and on the speculative side.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] The archaeological site **Abri de la Madeleine** (Magdalene Shelter) is a rock shelter under an overhanging cliff situated near Tursac, in the Dordogne *département* of the Aquitaine région of southwestern France.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] It represents the type site of the Magdalenian culture of the Upper Paleolithic.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] The shelter was also occupied during the Middle Ages.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] The medieval castle of Petit Marsac stands on the top of the cliff just above the shelter.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] Édouard Lartet, financed and helped by the Englishman Henry Christy, were the first systematic excavators of the site, starting in 1863, and published their findings in 1875 under the name of the Age of the Reindeer ("L'âge du renne").
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] Objects that were found at the **la Madeleine** site are distributed among a number of museums, including the Muséum de Toulouse, the Musee des Antiquites Nationales, St.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] The Abri de la Madeleine is classified as a *Monument historique* since 1956.
[src:acheulean/abri-de-la-madeleine] In 1979, the Abri de la Madeleine was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List as part of the *Prehistoric Sites and Decorated Caves of the Vézère Valley* because of its unique paleolithic artwork and archeological importance.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] It mostly incorporated the territories of Neo-Assyrian Empire corresponding to what is now northern Iraq in the upper Tigris, the middle and upper Euphrates, parts of modern-day northwestern Iran, modern-day northeastern Syria (Eber-Nari) and part of southeast Anatolia (now Turkey).
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] However, Egypt and the Sinai Peninsula were separate Achaemenid territories.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Between 609 and 559 BC, former Assyrian territories were divided between the Median Empire to the east and the Neo-Babylonian Empire to the west.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Both parts were subsumed into the Achaemenid Empire in 539 BC, and it has been argued that they constituted the satrapies of Media and Aθurā, respectively.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In Herodotus's account, the Ninth Tributary District comprised "Babylonia and the rest of Assyria" and excluded Eber-Nari.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Despite a few rebellions, Aθurā functioned as an important part of the Achaemenid Empire and its inhabitants were given the right to govern themselves throughout Achaemenid rule and Old Aramaic was used diplomatically by the Achaemenids.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Known for their combat skills, Assyrian soldiers (along with the Lydians) constituted the main heavy infantry of the Achaemenid military.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] This wealth was due to the land's great prosperity for agriculture that the Achaemenids used effectively for almost 200 years.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In contrast to the policy of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, the Achaemenid Persians did not intervene in the internal affairs of their ruling satrapies as long as they continued the flow of tribute and taxes back to Persia.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Battle of Nineveh in 612 BC eventually left Assyria destroyed for years to come.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrians continued to fight on with the aid of another of their former vassals, the Twenty-sixth Dynasty of Egypt, also known as the Saïte dynasty, who feared the rise of these new powers.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A costly but victorious Battle at Megiddo against the forces of the Kingdom of Judah in 609 allowed Saïte Egypt to advance to the rescue, only to be defeated by the Babylonian-Median-Scythian alliance.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Harran, the new Assyrian capital, was eventually taken the same year, thus ending the empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Despite this, part of the remnants of the former Assyrian army continued to fight on, along with Egypt, until final defeat at Carchemish in 605 BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Babylonian rule was unpopular but did not last long.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In 539, Cyrus the Great defeated the Babylonian king Nabonidus—ironically himself an Assyrian from Harran—took Babylon and made it, along with Assyria, into provinces of the new Achaemenid Empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The former major Assyrian capitals of Nineveh, Dur-Sharrukin and Kalhu (now Nimrud) were only sparsely populated during Achaemenid rule.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Most Assyrian settlement was in smaller cities, towns and villages at plain level, in the mountains, or on mounds such as Tell ed-Darim.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] However, according to more recent Assyriologists such as Georges Roux, cities such as Arrapḫa, Guzana (now the ruins of Tell Halaf) and Arbela (now Erbil) remained intact, and Ashur was to revive.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Despite many of the Assyrian cities being left largely in ruins from the battles that led to the fall of its empire in the seventh century BC, rural Assyria was prosperous according to the Greek scholar Xenophon.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] After passing Kalhu and Nineveh (which he described in ruins with only a handful of Assyrians dwelling amongst them), Xenophon and the Greeks turned north-west, following the east bank of the Tigris.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The testimony is an example of the rich agricultural resources of Assyria's region and the existence of a satrap's palace.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] It is not known exactly where this palace was located, but Austen Henry Layard suggested it may have been near Zakho.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Prior to the Persian rule of Assyria, the Achaemenids were greatly Assyrianized, and Aramaic continued as the lingua franca of the Empire in the region, with the Imperial Script the everyday writing system.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Traditional Mesopotamian religion within the empire was tolerated, and the judicial system, Assyrian calendar and imperial standards imposed by the Assyrians remained in force everywhere.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrians, like all other tributary peoples of the Achaemenids, were obliged to pay taxes to the Emperor and, whenever he campaigned, supply troops as well.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Reliefs of Assyrian tribute bearers carved on the east and north sides of the Apadana, consist of seven bearded men: one carrying animal skins, one carrying a length of cloth, two carrying bowls, and two leading mouflons.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrian Empire resorted to a policy of deporting troublesome conquered peoples (predominantly Aramean tribes as well as many Jews, Elamites and others) into Mesopotamia.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] While this allowed some integration, it may have also led to the various rebellions within the Empire in the seventh century.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] By the sixth century, the indigenous and originally Akkadian-speaking peoples of Assyria and Babylonia spoke Akkadian-influenced varieties of Eastern Aramaic that still survive among the Assyrian people to this day.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Consequently, during the Persian rule of Assyria, Aramaic gradually became the main language spoken by the Assyrians.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Even before the Empire fell, the Assyrians had made Aramaic language the *lingua franca* of its empire; many could speak it and the ruling elite of Assyria needed to be bilingual, capable of speaking both Akkadian and Aramaic.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The conquest of Assyria and the violent destruction of the cities meant that many of these bilingual skilled individuals died with their language and the Aramaic script was incorporated into the Assyrian culture by around the late 6th century BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Imperial Aramaic was highly standardized; its orthography was based more on historical roots than any spoken dialect, and the inevitable influence of Persian gave the language a new clarity and robust flexibility.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an "official language", noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the lingua franca of the Achaemenid territories, suggesting then that the Achaemenid-era use of Aramaic was more pervasive than generally thought.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] For centuries after the fall of the Achaemenids, Imperial Aramaic–or near enough for it to be recognizable–remained an influence on the various native Iranian languages.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Aramaic script and–as ideograms–Aramaic vocabulary survived as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi scripts.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] One of the largest collections of Imperial Aramaic texts is that of the Persepolis fortification tablets, which number about five hundred.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Many of the extant documents witnessing to this form of Aramaic come from Egypt, and from Elephantine in particular.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Of them, the best known is the *Wisdom of Ahiqar*, a book of instructive aphorisms quite similar in style to the biblical Book of Proverbs.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Achaemenid Aramaic is sufficiently uniform that it is often difficult to know where any particular example of the language was written.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Only careful examination reveals the occasional loan word from a local language.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A group of thirty Imperial Aramaic documents from Bactria were recently discovered, and an analysis was published in November 2006.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The texts, which were rendered on leather, reflect the use of Aramaic in the fourth century BC Achaemenid provinces of Bactria and Sogdia.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Aramaic dialects and written script survive to this day among the Christian Assyrians of Iraq, southeastern Turkey, northeastern Syria and northwestern Iran.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In 546 and 520 BC, the two Assyrian provinces of Mada and Athura revolted against the Achaemenids.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Though the revolts were suppressed, it illustrated that the two regions acted in unison, suggesting perhaps an ethnic and cultural link.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Having said this a rebellion could occur in several different parts of an Empire for geographical reasons and it may have been that the whole of the Mesopotamia region became swept with rebellion.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Although the effectiveness of the once invincible Assyrian army was shown to be greatly depleted by the time of its eventual collapse, the soldiers of Assyria continued to be brave and fierce warriors.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Most soldiers at the time would not wear heavy armour, but rather than act as melee troops, would serve as skirmishers.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrian troops were different, since they fought as archers, cavalry and heavy infantry and were useful as front line troops.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrian infantry was specifically trained to engage in hand-to-hand combat.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A massive army was assembled by Xerxes in the early 5th century BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Contemporary estimates place the numbers between 100,000 and over a million.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Whatever the number, it was enormous and the Persians summoned troops from all across their realm.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Herodotus remarks that Assyrian soldiers were employed in Xerxes's expedition to Greece.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrians were employed in the construction of this building, albeit with many other tributary peoples as well as Persians themselves.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The western Assyrians of Athura were closer to Mount Lebanon, where fine trees could be found and timber processed for Darius's grand Palace.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The eastern Assyrians of Mada were charged with excavating gold.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Assyrian influence over Achaemenid art and sculpture can be seen in various areas of the empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Examples include the doorway relief of the palaces in Pasargadae, and in the Bukan area (near Urmia) where various tiles are decorated with human-headed winged figures, lions, and ibexes.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The symbol of the Assyrian god Aššūr was chosen as the faravahar, the symbol of God in Zoroastrianism, during the Achaemenid rule of Assyria.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The best example of Assyrian influence can be observed in the Gate of All Nations in Persepolis, with two lamassus (human-headed winged bull) in the entrance.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Assyrian lamassu was used to protect the palace from evil spirits, while those of Persepolis expressed meditative calm and humanity.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Iranologists and Assyriologists have tried to answer the question of how was the influence transmitted.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Possibilities include contacts between Athura and Persia were frequent and Achaemenid architects visited the Assyrian palaces.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Other suggest Assyrian slaves were brought back to Persia to have them work on the new palaces.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] As with many other countries, the primary occupation was farming.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The large output of Mesopotamian farms resulted in highly populated civilizations.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The chief crop that fueled the ever-growing civilizations in the region was the grain barley and enumer wheat though sesame seeds also provided a source of nourishment.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Like much of the rest of the world at the time, the economy of Athura relied heavily upon the produce of the farms and the rivers, including fish and what fruit and meat could be raised in the Euphrates' fertile soils.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The agricultural year began with sowing after summer.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Flooding posed a serious risk to farmers, whilst rodents were supposedly driven off by prayers to the rodent god.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] To ensure that such prayers were answered, tall silos were built to house the grain and keep out the mice.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] To prevent the hot winds of the region from destroying the crops, tall palm trees were planted around the smaller trees, thus breaking the wind and shading the plants from the heat of the sun, the intensity of which provided plenty for the plants, even when shaded.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Following the Persian conquest, peaches were added to the original Assyrian mix of apples, cherries, figs, pears, plums and pomegranates.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Tree growing was an art mastered with tree-cutting and even "artificial mating" in order to have the Palm trees yield fruit.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In the north, rainfall in Athura met the demands of farming but in the more southernly parts (covering Mada) Shadufs were used to assist in irrigation.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Oxen, donkeys, cattle and sheep were raised, the latter for their milk (which could be turned into butter) and the former as draught animals.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Pigs, ducks, geese and chickens were all raised for their meat.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Hunting supplemented the food supply with birds and fish.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The down-time resulting from farming and the seasons allowed men and women to master other skills in life such as the arts, philosophy and leisure.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Without the fertile soils of the Euphrates river valley, civilization would not have come to be.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Kalhu (Nimrud)'s buildings were dramatically destroyed during the sacking of 614–612 BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] However, evidence of reoccupation during the "post-Assyrian period" (612–539 BC) is noted in various areas, including the Palace of Adad-nirari III, the North-West Palace, the Burnt Palace and Nabu Temple complex, Fort Shalmaneser, and the Town-Wall Houses.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Despite Xenephon's description of the city as being abandoned, archaeological evidence seems to show that there was some Achaemenid-period occupation.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Phase 3 or H in the Nabu Temple complex and Burnt Palace is described as Achaemenid occupation.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] They include traces of kilns on the south side of Room 47 in the Burnt Palace, together with red glass ingots and slag, which after a radiocarbon analysis yielded a date of 425 +/− 50 BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Also in the South-East Palace were two "eye of Horus" amulets, often regarded as hallmarks of Achaemenid period material culture.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Another eye of Horus amulet has been found in the Town Hall Houses.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In the palace of Adad-nirari III, three bronze kohl sticks with castellated heads having been identified as Achaemenid period.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Like other Assyrian capitals, Assur was greatly destroyed during the battles of the century before.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The importance of the city thereafter is not clear, but much evidence indicate it was a flourishing city during the Achaemenid rule.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] After the Babylonian conquest by Cyrus the Great, the "Cyrus Cylinder" mentions Assur as one of the cities of which cult statues were returned.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] At the Assur Temple, two shrines have been identified as being built between the fifth and third centuries BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A few graves at the site also may have been belonged to the Achaemenid period.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] From the grave site, a pair of circular earrings with globules has clearly been identified as Achaemenid.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] These earrings are similar to the silver earring found at Dur-Sharrukin near Nineveh.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In another grave, Haller dates grave number 811 as Achaemenid period.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The grave contained three bodies, a stamp-seal showing the goddess Ishtar standing on the back of a lion.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] This might indicate that ancient Mesopotamian religion was still being practiced within the Assyrian population during the Achaemenid rule.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Other objects from the grave 811 include a bronze fibula; another earring, but gold rather than the earlier described silver; different kinds of beads of silver, agate, frit and glass; an alabastron; a bowl made of copper; and two pottery bottles.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] It is not clear, however, if all the items are Achaemenid in date.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] To the northeast of Kirkuk, the site of Tel ed-Daim shows significant evidence of Achaemenid rule.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A small fortified palace (most probably for a local governor) includes a bronze wall-plaques, a bronze snaffle-bit of a type well known from Achaemenid contexts at Persepolis, kohl tubes with ribbed decoration tapering, and pottery.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The pottery in the palace show similarities with the pottery from Nimrud that has been identified as Achaemenid.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In the Eski Mosul Dam Salvage Project, a few items were identified as dating from the Achaemenid period.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The project was located to the northwest of Mosul, in the upper Tigris valley, and within the Assyrian heartland.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In the Kharabeh Shattani site, various amounts of pottery have been dated Achaemenid.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] These include four bowls of which have similarities of Achaemenid bowls in Susa and Pasargadae.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Other times include clay spindle whorls, two iron sickle blades, and a bronze plate optimistically identified as a horse's forehead plaque.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A bronze finger-ring with a crouching animal engraved on the bezel was also found in the site and is considered to be widespread in the Achaemenid empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Also in the project, a grave site excavated found bodies that included a conical kohl pot and a bronze pin with a castellated top.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] These objects are considered to be distinctive Achaemenid type.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In the late fourth century BC, Alexander the Great led his Greco-Macedonian army to conquer the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The empire's vast territory and numerous tributary peoples ensured that rebellion would be a constant problem.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] This new Greek Empire relied upon the administrative system put in place by the Persians to govern these new lands; consequently, the Assyrian lands of Athura and Mada were administrated as such by their own satraps.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] When Alexander the Great died, the Greek successor state of the Seleucid Empire, created in the Babylonian War, retained control of much of the Persian Empire.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The *Babylonian Chronicles* now show the vitality of Greek culture in ancient cities like Babylon.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Whilst Greek rule beyond the Euphrates was subject to constant and eventually successful Iranian incursions, Assyria was forced to take the role of a frontier province, first defending the Seleucid Empire against the Parthians and later defending the Parthian Empire against the Romans.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Greek rule in the East did not last long, although the cultural impact did - by the mid-third century BC, the satraps began revolting against the Seleucid Empire in Iran and Bactria, establishing their own domains.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] A temporary revival of Seleucid power reestablished Imperial authority in these regions in the late 3rd and early 2nd century BC, but afterward the Parthians came to incorporate the lands known as Assyria once again by the mid-second century BC.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Rule by the Parthian Empire aimed to emulate that of their Persian predecessors, the Achaemenids, with a similar system of administration involving satraps and smaller provinces.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Indeed, the main rebel behind the rise of Parthia from Seleucia was a satrap himself.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] On top of this, the Parthian Empire was more decentralized and power was shared amongst clan leaders, hinting at the possibility of the retention of the provinces.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Mesopotamia became the heartland of the Seleucid Empire with a new capital, Seleucia, founded.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] As a result, much culture and knowledge was exchanged between the Greeks and the Assyrians.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The invasions of Alexander the Great consisted not only of soldiers but scientists and historians.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Beginning in the first century BC, the Romans began expanding their Empire at the cost of the Parthians.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Initially, the nomadic military tactic of circling and shooting worked to deadly effect against the slow, heavy-moving infantry of the Romans.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In time, however, superior technology and strategy drove the Parthians out of the Mediterranean and most of Anatolia.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The Parthians continued to resist Roman rule, invading and in turn being invaded by the Romans many times, with their capital Ctesiphon being sacked three times.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] The consequence of these bloody and inconclusive wars meant that the Assyrian provinces bore the brunt of the fighting, with Assyrian troops fighting for one side and then, at the change of the governing of the lands of Mada and Athura, fighting for the other side.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Naturally such events served to undermine the Assyrians.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Assyrians had begun to adopt Christianity from the first century and Aramaic remained the spoken language of the region.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] By the second century AD, the Roman Empire under Trajan began to achieve the upper hand against the Parthians and established the province of Assyria along the Euphrates and Tigris.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] From AD 226, Assyria became a province of the Sasanian Empire and was known as Asōristān ("Asōr-land") in Middle Persian.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In 650, the area fell to the early Muslim conquests.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] However, the region remained Aramaic-speaking and largely Christian well into the Middle Ages.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Assyrians remain in the area to this day, and there are a number of Assyrian towns and villages in the region.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] In addition, cities such as Mosul, Dohuk, Erbil and Kirkuk have Assyrian populations.
[src:acheulean/achaemenid-assyria] Most Assyrians remain Christian and retain the Aramaic language and script.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Acheulean tools were produced during the Lower Palaeolithic era across Africa and much of West Asia, South Asia, East Asia and Europe, and are typically found with *Homo erectus* remains.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] It is thought that Acheulean technologies first developed about 2 million years ago, derived from the more primitive Oldowan technology associated with *Homo habilis*.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The Acheulean includes at least the early part of the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Its end is not well defined; if Sangoan (also known as Epi-Acheulean) is included, it may be taken to last until as late as 130,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In Europe and Western Asia, early Neanderthals utilized Acheulean technology, later transitioning to the more advanced Mousterian beginning around 320,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The type site for the Acheulean is Saint-Acheul, a suburb of Amiens, the capital of the Somme department in Picardy, where artifacts were found in 1859.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] John Frere is generally credited as being the first to suggest a very ancient date for Acheulean hand-axes.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In 1797, he sent two examples to the Royal Academy in London from Hoxne in Suffolk.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] He had found them in prehistoric lake deposits along with the bones of extinct animals and concluded that they were made by people "who had not the use of metals" and that they belonged to a "very ancient period indeed, even beyond the present world".
[src:acheulean/acheulean] His ideas were, however, ignored by his contemporaries, who subscribed to a pre-Darwinian view of human evolution.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Later, Jacques Boucher de Crèvecœur de Perthes, working between 1836 and 1846, collected further examples of hand-axes and fossilised animal bone from the gravel river terraces of the Somme near Abbeville in northern France.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Again, his theories attributing great antiquity to the finds were spurned by his colleagues, until one of de Perthes' main opponents, Marcel Jérôme Rigollot, began finding more tools near Saint Acheul.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Following visits to both Abbeville and Saint Acheul by the geologist Joseph Prestwich, the age of the tools was finally accepted.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In 1872, Louis Laurent Gabriel de Mortillet described the characteristic hand-axe tools as belonging to *L'Epoque de St Acheul*.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The industry was renamed as the Acheulean in 1925.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Providing calendrical dates and ordered chronological sequences in the study of early stone tool manufacture is often accomplished through one or more geological techniques, such as radiometric dating, often potassium-argon dating, and magnetostratigraphy.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] From the Konso Formation of Ethiopia, Acheulean hand-axes are dated to about 1.5 million years ago using radiometric dating of deposits containing volcanic ashes.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Acheulean tools in South Asia have also been found to be dated as far as 1.5 million years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] However, in 2003 examples of the Acheulean from the West Turkana region of Kenya were described which have been dated through the method of magnetostratigraphy to about 1.76 million years ago, and in 2023 finds from Ethiopia were reported dating to 1.95 million years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The earliest user of Acheulean tools may have been *Homo ergaster*, who first appeared about 1.8 million years ago (not all researchers use this formal name, and instead prefer to call these users *early Homo erectus*).
[src:acheulean/acheulean] However, it is impossible to know for sure whether *Homo ergaster* was the only maker of early Acheulean tools, since other hominin species, such as *Homo habilis*, also lived in East Africa at this time.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] From geological dating of sedimentary deposits, it appears that the Acheulean originated in Africa and spread to Asian, Middle Eastern, and European areas sometime between 1.5 million years ago and about 800 thousand years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In individual regions, this dating can be considerably refined; in Europe for example, it was thought that Acheulean methods did not reach the continent until around 500,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] However, more recent research demonstrated that hand-axes from Spain were made more than 900,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] It is therefore important not to see the Acheulean as a neatly defined period or one that happened as part of a clear sequence but as one tool-making technique that flourished especially well in early prehistory.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The enormous geographic spread of Acheulean techniques also makes the name unwieldy as it represents numerous regional variations on a similar theme.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The term Acheulean does not represent a common culture in the modern sense, rather it is a basic method for making stone tools that was shared across much of the Old World.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In Europe, the more advanced Mousterian utilizing the Levallois technique appeared around 320,000 years ago, and had displaced the Acheulean in Europe and the Middle East by around 125,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The Acheulean had also disappeared from Africa by this time.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The Acheulean may have lasted much later, until around 50,000 years ago in East Asia.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The Mode 1 industries created rough flake tools by hitting a suitable stone with a hammerstone.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The resulting flake that broke off would have a natural sharp edge for cutting and could afterwards be sharpened further by striking another smaller flake from the edge if necessary (known as "retouch").
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These early toolmakers may also have worked the stone they took the flake from (known as a core) to create chopper cores although there is some debate over whether these items were tools or just discarded cores.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Advanced, later Acheulean toolmakers supplemented stone-on-stone percussion by utilizing "soft hammer" percussion using bone, antler, or wood tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These type of hammers, compared to stone, yields more control over the shape of the finished tool, and can be used to resharpen blunted tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The oldest locality showing evidence of "soft hammer" percussion in Eurasia is the Boxgrove site in southern England, dating to around 480,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Soft hammer percussion may have emerged around the same time in Africa.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Unlike the earlier Mode 1 industries, it was the core that was prized over the flakes that came from it.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Another advance was that the Mode 2 tools were worked symmetrically and on both sides indicating greater care in the production of the final tool.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Mode 3 technology emerged towards the end of Acheulean dominance and involved the Levallois technique, most famously exploited by the Mousterian industry.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Transitional tool forms between the two are called Mousterian of Acheulean Tradition, or MTA types.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The long blades of the Upper Palaeolithic Mode 4 industries appeared long after the Acheulean was abandoned.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] As the period of Acheulean tool use is so vast, efforts have been made to classify various stages of it such as John Wymer's division into Early Acheulean, Middle Acheulean, Late Middle Acheulean and Late Acheulean for material from Britain.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These schemes are normally regional and their dating and interpretations vary.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In Africa, there is a distinct difference in the tools made before and after 600,000 years ago with the older group being thicker and less symmetric and the younger being more extensively trimmed.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The primary innovation associated with Acheulean hand-axes is that the stone was worked symmetrically and on both sides.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] For the latter reason, handaxes are, along with cleavers, bifacially worked tools that could be manufactured from the large flakes themselves or from prepared cores.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Tool types found in Acheulean assemblages include pointed, cordate, ovate, ficron, and bout-coupé hand-axes (referring to the shapes of the final tool), cleavers, retouched flakes, scrapers, and segmental chopping tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Materials used were determined by available local stone types; flint is most often associated with the tools but its use is concentrated in Western Europe; in Africa sedimentary and igneous rock such as mudstone and basalt were most widely used, for example.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Other source materials include chalcedony, quartzite, andesite, sandstone, chert, and shale.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Even relatively soft rock such as limestone could be exploited.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In all cases the toolmakers worked their handaxes close to the source of their raw materials, suggesting that the Acheulean was a set of skills passed between individual groups.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Some smaller tools were made from large flakes that had been struck from stone cores.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These flake tools and the distinctive waste flakes produced in Acheulean tool manufacture suggest a more considered technique, one that required the toolmaker to think one or two steps ahead during work that necessitated a clear sequence of steps to create perhaps several tools in one sitting.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] A hard hammerstone would first be used to rough out the shape of the tool from the stone by removing large flakes.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These large flakes might be re-used to create tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The tool maker would work around the circumference of the remaining stone core, removing smaller flakes alternately from each face.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The scar created by the removal of the preceding flake would provide a striking platform for the removal of the next.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Misjudged blows or flaws in the material used could cause problems, but a skilled toolmaker could overcome them.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Once the roughout shape was created, a further phase of flaking was undertaken to make the tool thinner.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The thinning flakes were removed using a softer hammer, such as bone or antler.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The softer hammer required more careful preparation of the striking platform and this would be abraded using a coarse stone to ensure the hammer did not slide off when struck.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Final shaping was then applied to the usable cutting edge of the tool, again using fine removal of flakes.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Some Acheulean tools were sharpened instead by the removal of a tranchet flake.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This was struck from the lateral edge of the hand-axe close to the intended cutting area, resulting in the removal of a flake running along (parallel to) the blade of the axe to create a neat and very sharp working edge.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This distinctive tranchet flake can be identified amongst flint-knapping debris at Acheulean sites.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Loren Eiseley calculated that Acheulean tools have an average useful cutting edge of 20 centimetres (8 inches), making them much more efficient than the 5 centimetres (2 inches) average of Oldowan tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] A wear analysis of handaxes from the 480,000 year old late Acheulean Boxgrove site in England found that they were primarily if not exclusively used for animal butchery, with no evidence for their use in woodworking or digging.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Alternative theories include a use for ovate hand-axes as a kind of hunting discus to be hurled at prey.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Puzzlingly, there are also examples of sites where hundreds of hand-axes, many impractically large and also apparently unused, have been found in close association together.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Sites such as Melka Kunturé in Ethiopia, Olorgesailie in Kenya, Isimila in Tanzania, and Kalambo Falls in Zambia have produced evidence that suggests Acheulean hand-axes might not always have had a functional purpose.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Recently, it has been suggested that the Acheulean tool users adopted the handaxe as a social artifact, meaning that it embodied something beyond its function of a butchery or wood cutting tool.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Knowing how to create and use these tools would have been a valuable skill and the more elaborate ones suggest that they played a role in their owners' identity and their interactions with others.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This would help explain the apparent over-sophistication of some examples which may represent a "historically accrued social significance".
[src:acheulean/acheulean] One theory goes further and suggests that some special hand-axes were made and displayed by males in search of a mate, using a large, well-made hand-axe to demonstrate that they possessed sufficient strength and skill to pass on to their offspring.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Once they had attracted a female at a group gathering, it is suggested that they would discard their axes, perhaps explaining why so many are found together.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This popular sexual selection hypothesis is controversial due to the assumptions made about sexual selection among extinct organisms.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Stone knapping with limited digital dexterity makes the center of mass the required direction of flake removal.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Physics then dictates a circular or oval end pattern, similar to the handaxe, for a leftover core after flake production.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This would explain the abundance, wide distribution, proximity to source, consistent shape, and lack of actual use, of these artifacts.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] showing important sites of the Acheulean industry (clickable map).
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The geographic distribution of Acheulean tools – and thus the peoples who made them – is often interpreted as being the result of palaeo-climatic and ecological factors, such as glaciation and the desertification of the Sahara Desert.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Acheulean stone tools have been found across the continent of Africa, save for the dense rainforest around the Congo River which is not thought to have been colonized by hominids until later.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] It is thought that from Africa their use spread north and east to Asia: from Anatolia, through the Arabian Peninsula, across modern day Iran and Pakistan, and into India, and beyond.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In Europe their users reached the Pannonian Basin and the western Mediterranean regions, modern day France, the Low Countries, western Germany, and southern and central Britain.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Areas further north did not see human occupation until much later, due to glaciation.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In Athirampakkam at Chennai in Tamil Nadu the Acheulean age started at 1.51 mya and it is also prior than North India and Europe.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Until the 1980s, it was thought that the humans who arrived in East Asia abandoned the hand-axe technology of their ancestors and adopted chopper tools instead.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] An apparent division between Acheulean and non-Acheulean tool industries was identified by Hallam L.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Movius, who drew the Movius Line across northern India to show where the traditions seemed to diverge.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Later finds of Acheulean tools at Chongokni in South Korea and also in Mongolia and China, however, cast doubt on the reliability of Movius's distinction.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Since then, a different division known as the Roe Line has been suggested.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] This runs across North Africa to Israel and thence to India, separating two different techniques used by Acheulean toolmakers.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] North and east of the Roe Line, Acheulean hand-axes were made directly from large stone nodules and cores; while, to the south and west, they were made from flakes struck from these nodules.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Possible Acheulean-like bifacial technologies have also been discussed in relation to the Arubo 1 site in General Tinio, Nueva Ecija, Philippines, where archaeologists recovered a proto-handaxe and bifacial cleaver made from locally sourced chert.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Pawlik noted that the proto-handaxe "would certainly be regarded as typical for the Early Acheulean" if found in regions traditionally associated with Acheulean industries.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The assemblage has been cited in broader discussions regarding the diversity of bifacial technologies in Southeast Asia and the limitations of strict interpretations of the Movius Line.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Most notably, however, it is *Homo ergaster* (sometimes called early *Homo erectus*), whose assemblages are almost exclusively Acheulean, who used the technique.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Later, the related species *Homo heidelbergensis* (the common ancestor of both Neanderthals and *Homo sapiens*) used it extensively.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Late Acheulean tools were still used by species derived from *H. erectus*, including *Homo sapiens idaltu* and early Neanderthals.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The symmetry of the hand-axes has been used to suggest that Acheulean tool users possessed the ability to use language; the parts of the brain connected with fine control and movement are located in the same region that controls speech.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The wider variety of tool types compared to earlier industries and their aesthetically as well as functionally pleasing form could indicate a higher intellectual level in Acheulean tool users than in earlier hominines.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Others argue that there is no correlation between spatial abilities in tool making and linguistic behaviour, and that language is not learned or conceived in the same manner as artefact manufacture.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Lower Palaeolithic finds made in association with Acheulean hand-axes, such as the Venus of Berekhat Ram, have been used to argue for artistic expression amongst the tool users.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The incised elephant tibia from Bilzingsleben in Germany, and ochre finds from Kapthurin in Kenya and Duinefontein in South Africa, are sometimes cited as being some of the earliest examples of an aesthetic sensibility in human history.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] There are numerous other explanations put forward for the creation of these artefacts; however, evidence of human art did not become commonplace until around 50,000 years ago, after the emergence of modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The kill site at Boxgrove in England is another famous Acheulean site.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Up until the 1970s these kill sites, often at waterholes where animals would gather to drink, were interpreted as being where Acheulean tool users killed game, butchered their carcasses, and then discarded the tools they had used.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Since the advent of zooarchaeology, which has placed greater emphasis on studying animal bones from archaeological sites, this view has changed.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Many of the animals at these kill sites have been found to have been killed by other predator animals, so it is likely that humans of the period supplemented hunting with scavenging from already dead animals.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Excavations at the Bnot Ya'akov Bridge site, located along the Dead Sea rift in the southern Hula Valley of northern Israel, have revealed evidence of human habitation in the area from as early as 750,000 years ago.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Archaeologists from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem claim that the site provides evidence of "advanced human behavior" half a million years earlier than has previously been estimated.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Their report describes an Acheulean layer at the site in which numerous stone tools, animal bones, and plant remains have been found.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Azykh cave located in Azerbaijan is another site where Acheulean tools were found.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In 1968, a lower jaw of a new type of hominid was discovered in the fifth layer (so-called Acheulean layer) of the cave.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Specialists named this type "Azykhantropus".
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Only limited artefactual evidence survives of the users of Acheulean tools other than the stone tools themselves.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Cave sites were exploited for habitation, but the hunter-gatherers of the Palaeolithic also possibly built shelters such as those identified in connection with Acheulean tools at Grotte du Lazaret and Terra Amata near Nice in France.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] The presence of the shelters is inferred from large rocks at the sites, which may have been used to weigh down the bottoms of tent-like structures or serve as foundations for huts or windbreaks.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] These stones may have been naturally deposited.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] In any case, a flimsy wood or animal skin structure would leave few archaeological traces after so much time.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Fire was seemingly being exploited by *Homo ergaster*, and would have been a necessity in colonising colder Eurasia from Africa.
[src:acheulean/acheulean] Conclusive evidence of mastery over it this early is, however, difficult to find.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The **Acheulo-Yabrudian complex** is a complex of archaeological cultures in the Levant at the end of the Lower Palaeolithic.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] It follows the Acheulian and precedes the Mousterian.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] It is also called the **Mugharan Tradition** or the **Acheulo-Yabrudian Cultural Complex (AYCC)**.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The Acheulo-Yabrudian complex has three stone-tool traditions, chronologically: the Acheulo-Yabrudian, the Yabrudian and the Pre-Aurignacian or Amudian.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The Yabrudian tradition is dominated by thick scrapers shaped by steep Quina retouch; the Acheuleo-Yabrudian contains Yabrudian scrapers and handaxes; and the Pre-Aurignacian/Amudian is dominated by blades and blade-tools.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] Determining the age period for the Acheulo-Yabrudian has been difficult as its major excavations occurred in the 1930s and 1950s, before modern radiometric dating.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The recently excavated Qesem and Tabun caves, however, suggest the oldest period is about 350 kyr and the most recent 200 kyr.
[src:acheulean/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] This would make the Lower–Middle Palaeolithic transition rapid occurring at 215,000 BP within a 30,000 year period.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The formation of the kingdom is obscure.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The first instance of a recorded Adiabenian ruler is in 69 BCE, when an unnamed king of Adiabene participated in the battle of Tigranocerta as an ally of the Armenian king Tigranes the Great (r.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] However, coinage implies the establishment of a kingdom in Adiabene around 164 BCE, following the disintegration of Greek Seleucid rule in the Near East.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene was conquered by the Parthian king Mithridates I (r.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] 171–132 BCE) between 145 and 141 BCE, and served at least from the reign of Mithridates II (r.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] 124–91 BCE) as an integral part of the Parthian realm.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabenian rulers converted to Judaism from paganism in the 1st century CE.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] According to the Talmud, both Helena and Monobaz donated large funds for the Temple of Jerusalem.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] After 115 CE, there are no historic traces of Jewish royalty in Adiabene.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The Parthians were overthrown by the Sasanian Empire in 224, who by the time of Shapur I (r.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] 240–270) had established their rule in Adiabene.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Ardashir II is the last figure to be recorded as king of Adiabene, which implies that the kingdom was after his tenure in c.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] 379 transformed into a province (*shahr*), governed by a non-royal delegate (*marzban* or *shahrab*) of the Sasanian king.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The name of the state entered English from the Ancient Greek Ἀδιαβηνή, which was derived from ܚܕܝܐܒ, **Ḥaḏy’aḇ** or **Ḥḏay’aḇ**, in Syriac.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The state was also known as *Nōdšīragān* or *Nōd-Ardaxšīragān* in Middle Persian, Նոր Շիրական, *Nor Shirakan*, in Armenian, and חַדְיָב, *Ḥaḏyāḇ*, in Hebrew.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene occupied a district in Median Empire between the Upper Zab (Lycus) and the Lower Zab (Caprus), though Ammianus Marcellinus speaks of Nineveh, Ecbatana, and Gaugamela as also belonging to it.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] By the late 1st century CE, its borders extended as far as Nisibis.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] In the Talmudic writings the name occurs as חדייב ,חדייף and הדייב.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Its chief city was Arbela (*Arba-ilu*), where Mar Uqba had a school, or the neighboring Hazzah, by which name the later Arabs also called Arbela.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] In Kiddushin 72a the Biblical Habor is identified with Adiabene, but in Jerusalem Talmud, Megillah i.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] 27, Ararat, Minni, and Ashkenaz are paraphrased by *Kordu*, *Harmini*, and *Hadayab*, i.e., Corduene, Armenia, and Adiabene; while in Ezekiel xxvii.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene had a mixed population of Assyrians, Arabs, Arameans, Greeks, Iranians, and Jews.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene was a major-speaking Syriac language kingdom.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] According to Pliny, four tribes inhabited the region of Adiabene: *Orontes*, *Alani*, *Azones* and *Silices*.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The account of Josephus' *Antiquities of the Jews* shows that there was a substantial Jewish population in the kingdom.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The difficult mixing of cultures can be seen in the story of the martyrdom of Mahanuš, a prominent Iranian Zoroastrian who converted to Christianity.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] In later times Adiabene became an archbishopric, with the seat of the metropolitan at Arbela.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The first known king of Adiabene was Abdissar who is known to scholarship only through his coinage, his Semitic name, meaning "the servant of Ishtar," suggests that he was of local Assyrian origin.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Based on the names of some Adiabenian rulers, Ernst Herzfeld suggested a Sakan or Scythian origin for the royal house of the kingdom; however, later progress in Iranian linguistic studies showed that these names were common west middle Iranian names.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] It has been suggested that the royal house of Adiabene, after fleeing Trajan's invasion, established the later Amatuni dynasty which ruled the area between the lakes Urmia and Van.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene was a district in Mesopotamia between upper and lower Zab and was a part of the Neo-Assyrian Empire and inhabited by Assyrians even after the fall of Nineveh.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] It was an integral part of Asoristan (Achaemenid and Sasanian Assyria).
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The region was later made a part of the Roman province of Assyria after the invasion by Trajan in 116.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Through an examination of Syriac source work, it can be seen that the population of Adiabene was Syriac speaking and of local Assyrian origin.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Despite this, Adiabene's elites were integrated with values of Zoroastrian social life through Sasanian culture.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] It can be assumed that many local Semitic cults succumbed to state supported Zoroastrianism during this period.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] This development can be seen Legend of Mar Qardagh, where the main protagonist is portrayed as being of Assyrian royal descent, yet a follower of the Zoroastrian faith prior to his conversion to Christianity.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Under the Achaemenid Persian kings, Adiabene seems for a time to have been a vassal state of the Persian Empire.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The Ten Thousand, an army of Greek mercenaries, retreated through Adiabene on their march to the Black Sea after the Battle of Cunaxa.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] According to Jewish tradition, Helena, the Queen of Adiabene converted to Judaism from paganism in the 1st century.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Queen Helena of Adiabene (known in Jewish sources as *Heleni HaMalka*) moved to Jerusalem where she built palaces for herself and her sons, Izates bar Monobaz and Monobaz II at the northern part of the city of David, south of the Temple Mount, and aided Jews in their war with Rome.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Queen Helena's sarcophagus was discovered in 1863.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] A pair of inscriptions on the sarcophagus, "tzaddan malka" and "tzadda malkata," is believed to be a reference to the provisions (tzeda in Hebrew) that Helena supplied to Jerusalem's poor and to the Jewish kingdom in general.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] According to Josephus, the queen converted to Judaism together with her son Monobaz II, under the influence of two Jews.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Another tradition has it that she met a Jewish jewelry merchant in Adiabene by the name of Hananiah (Ananias) or Eliezer, who told her about the people of Israel and persuaded her to join them.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] All historic traces of Jewish royalty in Adiabene ended around 115 CE, but these stories made a huge impact on rabbinic literature and Talmud.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Nominally Zoroastrian, the people of Adiabene were tolerant toward Judaism, and permitted the establishment of Jewish communities there.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The Jews of Edessa, Nisibis, and Adiabene repaid them by being among the most vigorous opponents of Trajan.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] In late second century Christianity rapidly spread among Zoroastrians and those formerly professing Judaism.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] When Christianity became the official religion of the Roman empire under Constantine, the position of Adiabenian Christians was naturally exacerbated, since they were seen as potentially disaffected by the zealously Zoroastrian Sasanians.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The little kingdom may have had a series of native rulers nominally vassal to the Macedonian, Seleucid and later Armenian (under Tigranes the Great) empires.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] It later became one of the client kingdoms of the Parthian empire.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] During the 1st century BCE and the 1st century CE, it gained a certain prominence under a series of kings descended from Monobaz I and his son Izates I.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Monobaz I is known to have been allied with king Abennerig of Characene, in whose court his son Izates II bar Monobaz lived for a time and whose daughter Symacho Izates married, as well as the rulers of other small kingdoms on the periphery of the Parthian sphere of influence.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The chief opponent of Trajan in Mesopotamia during the year 115 was the last king of independent Adiabene, Meharaspes.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] He had made common cause with Ma'nu (Mannus) of Singar (Singara).
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Trajan invaded Adiabene, and made it part of the Roman province of Assyria; under Hadrian in 117.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] In the summer of 195 Septimius Severus was again warring in Mesopotamia, and in 196 three divisions of the Roman army fell upon Adiabene.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] According to Dio Cassius, Caracalla took Arbela in the year 216, and searched all the graves there, wishing to ascertain whether the Arsacid kings were buried there.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Many of the ancient royal tombs were destroyed.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Despite the overthrow of the Parthians by the Sasanians in 224 CE, the feudatory dynasties remained loyal to the Parthians, and resisted Sasanian advance into Adiabene and Atropatene.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Due to this, and religious differences, Adiabene was never regarded as an integral part of Iran, even though the Sasanians controlled it for several centuries.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] After the Roman Empire gradually made Christianity its official religion during the fourth century, the inhabitants of Adiabene, who were primarily Assyrian Christians, sided with Christian Rome rather than the Zoroastrian Sasanians.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The Byzantine Empire sent armies to the region during the Byzantine–Sasanian wars, but this did nothing to change the territorial boundaries.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Adiabene remained a province of the Sasanians Empire until the Muslim conquest of Persia.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The region was recorded as *Nod-Ardadkhshiragan* or *Nod-Ardashiragan* in Sasanian period.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Between the 5th and the 14th centuries Adiabene was a metropolitan province of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The *Chronicle of Erbil*, a purported history of Christianity in Adiabene under the Parthians and Sasanians, lists a number of early bishops of Erbil.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] The authenticity of the *Chronicle of Erbil* has been questioned, and scholars remain divided on how much credence to place in its evidence.
[src:acheulean/adiabene] Some of the bishops in the following list are attested in other sources, but the early bishops are probably legendary.
[src:acheulean/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:acheulean/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:acheulean/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:acheulean/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:acheulean/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:acheulean/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:acheulean/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:acheulean/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:acheulean/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:acheulean/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:acheulean/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:acheulean/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:acheulean/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:acheulean/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:acheulean/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:acheulean/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:acheulean/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:acheulean/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:acheulean/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:acheulean/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:acheulean/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:acheulean/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:acheulean/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:acheulean/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:acheulean/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:acheulean/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:acheulean/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:acheulean/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:acheulean/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:acheulean/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:acheulean/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:acheulean/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:acheulean/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:acheulean/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:acheulean/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:acheulean/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:acheulean/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:acheulean/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:acheulean/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:acheulean/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:acheulean/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:acheulean/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:acheulean/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:acheulean/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:acheulean/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:acheulean/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:acheulean/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:acheulean/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:acheulean/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:acheulean/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:acheulean/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
